Configure GitHub Actions for Continuous Integration

01
On this page
  1. Reviewing Commands in package.json
  2. Configuring GitHub Actions
    1. Looking at node.js.yml
  3. GitHub Actions in the Browser
  4. Push Changes to Run Tests Again
  5. 🛠 Challenge: Disable Cypress Screenshots for CI
  6. 🛠 Solution: Update cypress.json Config

As we push code to our application repos, it’s important to make sure that fixes in one place don’t cause issues in another.

Continuous Integration is a process that will automatically run our test suites as the code is pushed, and prevent deployment if the tests fail. This gives us backup coverage in case some members of our team forget to test before committing their code.

In this section, we will set up GitHub Actions to handle our continuous integration workflow. There are different CI providers out there with their own setup instructions, but the general idea is the same.

Reviewing Commands in package.json

We have several scripts inside of package.json that run our tests.

As you’ll recall, the test and test:puppeteer scripts run Jest in our terminal and exit on their own. But when running Cypress and Cypress Component Testing, a UI is loaded in the browser for us to interact with.

In order to allow for these tests to run in GitHub actions, we create scripts that call Cypress with the run command instead of the open command. These scripts have :ciappended to their names:

// inside of package.json
"scripts": {
	...
	"cypress:run": "npx cypress run",
	"test:components:ci": "npx cypress run-ct"
	...
}
// inside of package.json
"scripts": {
	...
	"cypress:run": "npx cypress run",
	"test:components:ci": "npx cypress run-ct"
	...
}

Configuring GitHub Actions

In the root of our project is a hidden .github directory that has a workflows directory nested inside of it. This is where the workflow configuration files live.

GitHub provides examples of different workflow configurations, including a Node.js example that I used as the base for the CampSpots project.

Looking at node.js.yml

Open the node.js.yml file inside of .github/workflows.

This YAML file tells GitHub Actions to checkout the repo, and install our project dependencies on the latest version of Ubuntu.

At the bottom of the file is where we specify task names and the corresponding package.json scripts to run them:

# at the bottom of node.js.yml

- name: Install modules
	run: yarn
- name: Run unit tests
  run: yarn test
- name: Run Cypress component tests
  run: yarn test:components:ci
- name: Run Cypress tests
  run: yarn test:ci
# at the bottom of node.js.yml

- name: Install modules
	run: yarn
- name: Run unit tests
  run: yarn test
- name: Run Cypress component tests
  run: yarn test:components:ci
- name: Run Cypress tests
  run: yarn test:ci

GitHub Actions in the Browser

If there’s an issue with a commit that you’ve pushed to your repo, GitHub will display a red “X” icon. If you click this icon, you’ll see a message related to the issue.

Following the “Details” link, the GitHub Actions screen opens and shows where the failure takes place:

Note that the errors you would see in GitHub Actions are the same as what you would see in your computer’s terminal– but in the cloud.

Push Changes to Run Tests Again

When changes are pushed to GitHub, the CI process will run again.

GitHub actions has been configured to cache the packages it installs, so subsequent CI runs should be faster.

Just like on your own machine, sometimes the console may log out some warnings but this won’t affect a test passing.

However, there is an error happening in GitHub Actions that stops our tests from completing.

Cypress is trying to take screenshots when a test fails, which isn’t supported by GitHub Actions.

A configuration update will fix it!

🛠 Challenge: Disable Cypress Screenshots for CI

Reference the Cypress Docs for screenshots and videos and disable screenshots so the GitHub Actions CI completes successfully.

🛠 Solution: Update cypress.json Config

To disable screenshots, update cypress.json to set screenshotOnRunFailure to be false :

{
    "component": {
        "componentFolder": "exercise2-cypress-components",
        "testFiles": "**/*test.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}"
    },
    "integrationFolder": "exercise3-cypress-integration",
    "testFiles": "**/*.test.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}",
    "video": false,
		"screenshotOnRunFailure": false
}
{
    "component": {
        "componentFolder": "exercise2-cypress-components",
        "testFiles": "**/*test.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}"
    },
    "integrationFolder": "exercise3-cypress-integration",
    "testFiles": "**/*.test.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}",
    "video": false,
		"screenshotOnRunFailure": false
}
